data.name: LblDisplayercontent.Text
data.value:
The Displayer is located on the top left portion of the screen. Upon loading the program, it shows a list of every Pokemon in numerical order. The list box contained in the Displayer is broken up into five columns:
- Number: is the number of the Pokemon - Name: is the name of the Pokemon - Type 1: is the first type of the Pokemon - Type 2: is the second type of the Pokemon, if there is one - Have: is whether or not the Pokemon is owned (useful for those who play the real game)
The Displayer also displays Pokemon from the Search function (see Search tab) and is able to change the type of sort. The Displayer can sort all the Pokemon, or ones that fit the parameters of the Search function in three ways:
- By number - By decending alphabetical order - By ascending alphabetical order
Pokemon selected from the Displayer will become the active Pokemon in the Selector.

data.name: label1.Text
data.value:
The Search function is accessed by clicking the "Search" button in the Displayer group. The Search function allows you to isolate Pokemon with specific traits and display them in the Displayer. The Search function can search using a maximum of four traits:
- Number: between two given numbers - Name: Letter(s) in which the name of the Pokemon begins with (case sensitive) - Types: having two specific types (not respective to Type 1/Type 2) - By have: whether or not the Pokemon is owned
Numbers can be selected through the combo box or typed manually. Leave at 1 to 493 if you do not want to search by number. Name must be typed manually. Leave blank if you do not want to search by name. can be selected through the combo box or typed manually, case sensitive. Leave one or both blank if you want to search for one type or do not want to search by type, respectively. Check "Search by have" and select whether you want to search for Pokemon owned or needed. Leave "Search by have" blank if you do not want to search by have. The Search function will then display all Pokemon within these parameters.

data.name: LblSelectorcontent.Text
data.value:
The Selector is located on top the right portion of the screen. The Selector displays the active Pokemon selected from the Displayer or from within the Selector. The selecter allows a Pokemon to be selected by three methods:
- By selecting it in the Displayer - By selecting a number from the "Number" combo box - By selecting a name from the "Name" combo box (sorted by number)
The selector shows the number, name, types, have value sprite of the selected Pokemon. The "Have" value is changes within the Selector. If a Pokemon is owned, check the "Have" check box and then then "Save" button to show that it is owned in the displayer and so that next time the program is opened, it will remember that that Pokemon is owned.
The "Add to team" button is also located in the Selector. If pressed, you will be prompted to give the new team member a nickname and a shiny value. Nicknames will not be used if the text box is left blank or the "No nickname" check box is checked. The shiny value determines if the new team member is "shiny" (of a different colour then normal).

data.name: LblTeamcontent.Text
data.value:
The Team is located at the bottom portion of the screen. The Team group displays the active team and its members. By adding team members from the Selector, a team of six Pokemon can be built. Each member's Pokemon name, nickname, types and sprite are displayed. The radio button next to each member determines the active team member. Teams can be saved or opened as text files through the toolbar at the top of the screen. You may also clear the current team, add a Pokemon from the Selector and remove the active member from the toolbar. Active members can be manipulated in three ways:
- Moved left, if not in first position - Moved right, if not in last position - Removed from team
By clicking the "Play" button, you can open the Stats Visualizer to compare the stats of your team members.

data.name: LblStatscontent.Text
data.value:
The Stats Visualizer appears in a new screen when the "Play" button is clicked below the Team group. The Visualizer can only be run if at least one member is on the active team. The more members, the more effective the Visualizer is. The Visualizer can simulate three stats:
- Attack: simulated by knocking a target off the screen - Defence: simulated by being the last member to be knocked off the screen - Speed: simulated by a race to the other side of the screen
The Visualizer uses a combination of actual constant stats individual to every Pokemon and random numbers, so generally the same Pokemon will beat out the others in one particular stat, but not always, especially if stats are close.
To simulate the trait, first select the stat you would like to simulate, then set the team on the screen. If stat is changed before you begin the simulation and after you set the team, you will have to reset the team. Press "Start" begin the simulation. Some simulations will take longer than others depending on stat being simulated and the stats of the Pokemon.

data.name: LblAboutcontent.Text
data.value:
This program was written entirely by Scott Mastromatteo. Toolbar images were made by me. The attack thing in the Stats Visualizer was also made by me.
Pokemon sprites were downloaded from websites and are owned by Nintendo.
I want to thank whomever named each image after the Pokemon number. Regular sprites and regular shiny sprites came from one source and the small icons came from another site.
Text file information came from tables on the Internet and were complied into one file by a program that I also wrote (a lot easier than typing out every name, number and type).
All Pokemon names are also owned by Nintendo.
